00:35:04.869 --> 00:35:07.505
Hogan shelters.
and I kind of really want

556
00:35:07.606 --> 00:35:08.873
to lean towards that design.

557
00:35:08.907 --> 00:35:12.210
[breathing heavily]

558
00:35:12.243 --> 00:35:16.648
Think log cabin. but instead
of tall. it's wide and short.

559
00:35:16.681 --> 00:35:18.383
It will still have four walls.

560
00:35:18.483 --> 00:35:20.852
and it'll have
a small dome on top.

561
00:35:20.885 --> 00:35:22.354
♪

562
00:35:30.328 --> 00:35:32.364
I felt very strongly going
into this competition

563
00:35:32.397 --> 00:35:35.600
that I wanted to have a shelter
that had a central fire.

564
00:35:35.634 --> 00:35:39.237
Having a central fire is
going to maximize your warmth.

565
00:35:39.270 --> 00:35:41.272
This shelter gives me
enough space

566
00:35:41.306 --> 00:35:45.176
to be able to stretch
out and relax my body.

567
00:35:45.276 --> 00:35:49.280
and store the things that
I need immediate access to

568
00:35:49.280 --> 00:35:52.751
while still just maximizing
how warm it could get

569
00:35:52.784 --> 00:35:54.619
in the really
extreme temperatures.

570
00:36:02.861 --> 00:36:04.963
Oh. my God!

571
00:36:06.297 --> 00:36:07.932
Cameron?

572
00:36:08.900 --> 00:36:11.036
Oh!

573
00:36:11.069 --> 00:36:12.837
Oh. my God.

574
00:36:15.040 --> 00:36:16.908
Are you all right?

575
00:36:19.844 --> 00:36:22.313
Oh. buddy.

576
00:36:22.347 --> 00:36:24.482
Why didn't you say something?

577
00:36:25.550 --> 00:36:26.818
Oh.

578
00:36:30.555 --> 00:36:32.290
You gotta speak up more.

579
00:36:36.928 --> 00:36:38.530
[bleep].

580
00:36:38.563 --> 00:36:44.369
♪

581
00:36:56.715 --> 00:36:58.683
♪

582
00:37:01.619 --> 00:37:04.556
[tense music]

583
00:37:04.589 --> 00:37:06.991
♪

584
00:37:07.092 --> 00:37:08.159
[Jacks] Oh. my God.

585
00:37:08.193 --> 00:37:09.327
Oh. my God.

586
00:37:09.360 --> 00:37:11.096
Oh. my God.
Oh. my God. Oh. my God.

587
00:37:11.129 --> 00:37:12.997
I got a hare.
I got a hare.

588
00:37:13.031 --> 00:37:14.899
I got a hare.
Oh. my God.

589
00:37:14.933 --> 00:37:16.601
Oh. my [bleep] God.

590
00:37:16.601 --> 00:37:17.635
Oh. my God.

591
00:37:18.837 --> 00:37:20.205
Hey. buddy.

592
00:37:23.842 --> 00:37:25.276
Thank you. Lord.

593
00:37:25.310 --> 00:37:27.045
Thank you. universe.

594
00:37:31.149 --> 00:37:33.485
[exhales]

595
00:37:33.518 --> 00:37:35.787
[sniffles] Thank you.

596
00:37:35.820 --> 00:37:41.359
♪

597
00:37:41.359 --> 00:37:42.861
It's funny.

598
00:37:42.894 --> 00:37:46.631
I have spent more time
in a drive-through

599
00:37:46.631 --> 00:37:51.169
waiting for a meal
than I did getting the hare.

600
00:37:51.202 --> 00:37:54.873
And this is only showing me
that taking the bow

601
00:37:54.906 --> 00:37:56.641
was the right decision.

602
00:37:56.674 --> 00:38:00.512
And now more than ever.
I can say. yeah. I'm a hunter.

603
00:38:00.545 --> 00:38:07.552
♪

604
00:38:09.954 --> 00:38:12.524
Marksmanship is
something that

605
00:38:12.557 --> 00:38:17.829
I've always wanted to be
better at.

606
00:38:17.862 --> 00:38:20.632
Before I was dropped off.

607
00:38:20.632 --> 00:38:24.135
salt was actually
my tenth item.

608
00:38:25.537 --> 00:38:26.538
OK.

609
00:38:26.571 --> 00:38:28.373
Salt's a multi-tool.

610
00:38:28.406 --> 00:38:30.141
Salt is electrolytes.

611
00:38:30.241 --> 00:38:31.609
It's flavoring.

612
00:38:31.643 --> 00:38:33.845
It can heal wounds.

613
00:38:33.878 --> 00:38:35.280
Oh.

614
00:38:35.280 --> 00:38:37.015
♪

615
00:38:37.048 --> 00:38:38.750
There's another kidney.

616
00:38:40.285 --> 00:38:41.419
Yum.

617
00:38:42.287 --> 00:38:43.721
Oh.

618
00:38:43.755 --> 00:38:47.358
So I felt very strongly
about taking salt.

619
00:38:47.358 --> 00:38:50.595
And then I was bringing
a bow as an alt item.

620
00:38:52.230 --> 00:38:54.966
I could have been convinced
to take it.

621
00:38:54.966 --> 00:38:58.636
And during orientation camp.
I was.

622
00:38:58.670 --> 00:39:00.038
Oh.

623
00:39:00.038 --> 00:39:02.040
♪

624
00:39:02.040 --> 00:39:04.175
The taste of success.

625
00:39:05.476 --> 00:39:06.845
Phew.

626
00:39:06.878 --> 00:39:11.216
And I am glad because
that bow got me food.

627
00:39:11.249 --> 00:39:12.350
Liver's my favorite.

628
00:39:12.450 --> 00:39:13.751
Saving the best for last.

629
00:39:13.852 --> 00:39:16.888
I think that there's
a power in it.

630
00:39:16.921 --> 00:39:19.357
and not just marksmanship.

631
00:39:19.357 --> 00:39:21.793
in being a hunter.

632
00:39:21.893 --> 00:39:24.329
a person who can provide.

633
00:39:24.362 --> 00:39:27.398
a person who can
come out on top.

634
00:39:27.398 --> 00:39:30.201
♪

635
00:39:30.235 --> 00:39:32.437
Look at my new additions
to our home.

636
00:39:34.038 --> 00:39:36.341
Yeah. it's just the one hare.

637
00:39:36.441 --> 00:39:40.044
but it's a sign that
I might be OK.

638
00:39:41.279 --> 00:39:44.282
It's a sign that I might
be here for the long haul.

639
00:39:46.718 --> 00:39:50.121
It's a sign that
I'm good enough to do this.

640
00:39:52.590 --> 00:39:55.293
Getting this hare was
a really good sign.

641
00:39:57.662 --> 00:39:59.364
To be continued.

642
00:39:59.397 --> 00:40:06.437
♪

643
00:40:19.517 --> 00:40:20.652
- Here we go.

644
00:40:23.955 --> 00:40:27.892
Had a pretty vivid dream
last night.

645
00:40:27.926 --> 00:40:30.595
I was here. but I had my phone

646
00:40:30.628 --> 00:40:32.964
and. um.

647
00:40:32.964 --> 00:40:35.566
I got a text from my wife

648
00:40:35.600 --> 00:40:37.201
and she said.

649
00:40:37.201 --> 00:40:40.638
"I feel lost.
I feel hopeless."

650
00:40:40.638 --> 00:40:41.673
That was the word.

651
00:40:41.773 --> 00:40:43.942
♪

652
00:40:44.042 --> 00:40:46.811
And then I woke up.

653
00:40:46.844 --> 00:40:48.513
♪

654
00:40:48.513 --> 00:40:52.016
Her aapa. her dad.
maybe yesterday was

655
00:40:52.116 --> 00:40:55.320
his last day. um.
here on Earth.

656
00:40:56.487 --> 00:40:59.190
And that could have been
the world's way of telling me.

657
00:40:59.290 --> 00:41:01.826
♪

658
00:41:01.826 --> 00:41:06.164
Her aapa pretty much taught me
a lot in my adult life

659
00:41:06.197 --> 00:41:11.002
about the Iñupiaq lifestyle.
the old Iñupiaq ways.

660
00:41:11.002 --> 00:41:12.437
Yeah. he means a lot to me.

661
00:41:12.437 --> 00:41:17.842
He's more of a father
than I've ever had.

662
00:41:17.842 --> 00:41:20.645
He's been the biggest--

663
00:41:20.678 --> 00:41:23.448
biggest role model

664
00:41:23.481 --> 00:41:25.450
my entire life. I would say.

665
00:41:25.483 --> 00:41:27.618
And. um.

666
00:41:27.652 --> 00:41:28.920
someone I'm going to
be thinking about.

667
00:41:28.953 --> 00:41:30.321
I hope that's not the case.

668
00:41:30.321 --> 00:41:35.259
But if that happened. then

669
00:41:35.293 --> 00:41:37.395
that's not good.

670
00:41:39.597 --> 00:41:43.368
So yeah. first thing I'm going
to do is finish the ivrulik.

671
00:41:43.401 --> 00:41:44.869
I have the roof to do.

672
00:41:44.969 --> 00:41:47.805
And then. uh. I can move in.

673
00:41:47.805 --> 00:41:54.645
♪

674
00:41:57.749 --> 00:42:00.084
My father-in-law.
his name is Elmer.

675
00:42:00.118 --> 00:42:03.755
His Iñupiaq name
is [speaking Iñupiaq].

676
00:42:03.788 --> 00:42:05.056
[grunts]

677
00:42:05.089 --> 00:42:06.958
There's one.

678
00:42:06.991 --> 00:42:09.060
What I really love
about my father-in-law.

679
00:42:09.160 --> 00:42:12.930
he's just a really
genuine Iñupiaq man

680
00:42:12.964 --> 00:42:16.200
who grew up
with Iñupiaq culture.

681
00:42:16.234 --> 00:42:18.102
old Iñupiaq traditions

682
00:42:18.202 --> 00:42:21.506
that not a lot
of people know about.

683
00:42:21.606 --> 00:42:23.408
Now

684
00:42:23.441 --> 00:42:28.346
we can position it
into place.

685
00:42:28.379 --> 00:42:31.315
He's taught me more
than my father ever had.

686
00:42:31.315 --> 00:42:34.485
And. uh. he's my father.

687
00:42:34.519 --> 00:42:35.420
he's my aapa.

688
00:42:35.453 --> 00:42:36.954
I call him aapa. too.

689
00:42:36.988 --> 00:42:38.790
Perfect.

690
00:42:38.890 --> 00:42:40.925
I instantly had
a connection with him.

691
00:42:40.958 --> 00:42:43.828
and he took me in as a son.

692
00:42:43.861 --> 00:42:45.763
He was immediately
teaching me how to

693
00:42:45.797 --> 00:42:48.566
live the old Iñupiaq way.

694
00:42:48.599 --> 00:42:51.202
♪

695
00:42:51.235 --> 00:42:54.539
And just thinking about him
and realizing.

696
00:42:54.639 --> 00:42:56.174
you know.
he's lived a long life.

697
00:42:56.207 --> 00:42:57.708
a long. beautiful life.

698
00:42:57.742 --> 00:42:59.911
He's--he's in his mid-80s.

699
00:42:59.944 --> 00:43:01.646
He's not going
to live forever.

700
00:43:01.679 --> 00:43:03.748
And. um. we all realize that.

701
00:43:03.781 --> 00:43:05.650
And we all realize that
every moment with him

702
00:43:05.683 --> 00:43:08.853
is precious. it is special.

703
00:43:08.886 --> 00:43:10.521
Beautiful.

704
00:43:10.521 --> 00:43:11.789
OK.

705
00:43:11.789 --> 00:43:13.524
We're going to get moved in
to this ivrulik.

706
00:43:13.558 --> 00:43:16.160
♪

707
00:43:16.160 --> 00:43:19.630
We'll start hauling
sleeping poles.

708
00:43:20.631 --> 00:43:22.834
Moving out.

709
00:43:22.867 --> 00:43:26.037
I'm most afraid of never
seeing my family again.

710
00:43:26.070 --> 00:43:30.741
I know that there are
dangers on this land.

711
00:43:30.775 --> 00:43:33.845
and that I may never return
home to my children again.

712
00:43:35.246 --> 00:43:37.949
But I've accepted that.

713
00:43:37.982 --> 00:43:41.619
I realized that
for thousands of years.

714
00:43:41.719 --> 00:43:46.457
Iñupiaq hunters would go out
in order to harvest food

715
00:43:46.491 --> 00:43:49.827
for their families
and their communities.

716
00:43:49.827 --> 00:43:53.164
and they might not
ever make it back.

717
00:43:53.197 --> 00:43:54.499
There we go.

718
00:43:54.599 --> 00:43:57.201
They might not know
if that was going

719
00:43:57.235 --> 00:44:00.438
to be the last time that
they saw their loved ones.

720
00:44:00.438 --> 00:44:03.040
This is the once-in-a-lifetime
opportunity

721
00:44:03.074 --> 00:44:06.344
to represent my culture.

722
00:44:06.444 --> 00:44:09.280
and I'm willing to die
to show the world

723
00:44:09.280 --> 00:44:11.849
who we are and who we've been.

724
00:44:13.351 --> 00:44:14.452
Hmm.

725
00:44:15.753 --> 00:44:17.722
Beautiful in here.

726
00:44:19.357 --> 00:44:21.792
I just feel so at peace.

727
00:44:26.631 --> 00:44:28.733
[tense music]

728
00:44:28.733 --> 00:44:34.872
♪

729
00:44:35.239 --> 00:44:38.509
[Ziga] OK. guys.
let's build a bridge.

730
00:44:38.609 --> 00:44:40.077
♪

731
00:44:40.111 --> 00:44:41.679
Here is the place.

732
00:44:41.712 --> 00:44:46.851
♪

733
00:44:46.884 --> 00:44:48.219
Nice.

734
00:44:51.522 --> 00:44:53.524
Let's see what's underwater.

735
00:45:08.439 --> 00:45:10.141
It's interesting to see.

736
00:45:10.241 --> 00:45:12.043
I hope I don't fall in water.

737
00:45:24.288 --> 00:45:27.491
OK. that's enough
of aquatic biology.

738
00:45:31.562 --> 00:45:34.832
♪

739
00:45:34.865 --> 00:45:38.603
My idea is to set
all the wire I have.

740
00:45:38.636 --> 00:45:40.438
as many snares as possible.

741
00:45:46.177 --> 00:45:47.845
♪

742
00:45:47.878 --> 00:45:50.281
When I put ten snares
and check the next morning.

743
00:45:50.314 --> 00:45:51.716
there were two hares there.

744
00:45:51.749 --> 00:45:53.851
And then next time
I put even more and more.

745
00:45:53.884 --> 00:45:56.520
So 45 is the number now.

746
00:45:58.122 --> 00:46:00.758
When I was young.
I kind of listed down

747
00:46:00.758 --> 00:46:02.760
what I would like
to do in life.

748
00:46:02.793 --> 00:46:07.031
and I wanted to be
an expert in one area.

749
00:46:07.064 --> 00:46:09.734
There were two big passions
for me. and one was.

750
00:46:09.767 --> 00:46:11.636
of course. bushcraft.

751
00:46:11.669 --> 00:46:15.473
and another one was
underwater life.

752
00:46:15.473 --> 00:46:19.710
And only one looked likely
to get me a job.

753
00:46:19.744 --> 00:46:22.413
And so I became
a fish biologist.

754
00:46:22.446 --> 00:46:25.416
♪

755
00:46:33.424 --> 00:46:37.962
The best thing about my job
is the research.

756
00:46:37.995 --> 00:46:42.166
OK. funny tree formation.

757
00:46:45.436 --> 00:46:49.807
I'm very analytical
about stuff in general.

758
00:46:49.840 --> 00:46:53.444
But now.
having this time out here.

759
00:46:53.477 --> 00:46:58.783
I can reanalyze where I was
successful and where not.

760
00:46:58.816 --> 00:47:02.119
And I have realized that
it's much more important

761
00:47:02.119 --> 00:47:06.357
to understand why something is
working in this way.

762
00:47:06.390 --> 00:47:08.359
or should be done in this way.

763
00:47:09.593 --> 00:47:11.929
Once you understand things.

764
00:47:11.962 --> 00:47:13.664
it's also much easier

765
00:47:13.698 --> 00:47:17.368
to give slight improvements
or adaptations

766
00:47:17.401 --> 00:47:19.403
according to the situation.

767
00:47:22.907 --> 00:47:24.108
OK.

768
00:47:26.377 --> 00:47:28.479
Now let's go berry picking.

769
00:47:28.512 --> 00:47:33.884
♪

770
00:47:33.884 --> 00:47:34.885
Oh.

771
00:47:34.919 --> 00:47:41.959
♪

772
00:47:49.567 --> 00:47:52.603
The reason why I'm
doing this competition is

773
00:47:52.603 --> 00:47:55.005
not only my personal challenge.

774
00:47:55.005 --> 00:47:59.276
but I'm doing it as
a researcher. as a scientist.

775
00:47:59.310 --> 00:48:01.645
This series created
a lot of knowledge.

776
00:48:01.679 --> 00:48:05.349
I would like to contribute
to this knowledge.

777
00:48:05.383 --> 00:48:07.051
From academic perspective.

778
00:48:07.084 --> 00:48:10.788
you really see what happens
to your body.

779
00:48:10.788 --> 00:48:13.758
These are really
extreme conditions

780
00:48:13.791 --> 00:48:15.626
that there is no other way
that people

781
00:48:15.659 --> 00:48:18.529
would go in these situations
and to monitor this.

782
00:48:18.562 --> 00:48:22.833
And you can really have
a proper scientific approach.

783
00:48:22.933 --> 00:48:25.603
This would be really
valuable information.

784
00:48:25.636 --> 00:48:30.007
not only for bushcraft.
but also for medicine

785
00:48:30.040 --> 00:48:33.277
or maybe even
for space exploration.

786
00:48:33.310 --> 00:48:37.181
pushing the limits
of what human body can stand.

787
00:48:37.281 --> 00:48:42.153
It's really valuable. the data
that actually exists here.

788
00:48:42.253 --> 00:48:43.954
[sighs]

789
00:48:46.724 --> 00:48:50.161
A bit of berries. a bit of sun.

790
00:48:51.629 --> 00:48:54.732
And...

791
00:48:54.765 --> 00:48:56.600
you can feel so much better.

792
00:48:59.170 --> 00:49:01.338
[makes moose call]

793
00:49:02.973 --> 00:49:04.775
[makes moose call]

794
00:49:08.646 --> 00:49:12.883
OK. regarding the position.

795
00:49:12.917 --> 00:49:15.586
there's my shelter.

796
00:49:15.686 --> 00:49:18.823
This is. unfortunately.
kind of peninsula.

797
00:49:18.923 --> 00:49:23.227
So lake goes
all the way around.

798
00:49:23.260 --> 00:49:26.030
So it's a bit unlikely that
moose--unless. I mean.

799
00:49:26.130 --> 00:49:28.866
there is kind of separation
between two lakes.

800
00:49:28.966 --> 00:49:32.269
So it might swim over.

801
00:49:32.303 --> 00:49:35.606
but I think
this wouldn't happen.

802
00:49:35.606 --> 00:49:38.676
But the good point is.

803
00:49:38.709 --> 00:49:42.680
here. it's like
this 2-meter channel.

804
00:49:42.713 --> 00:49:46.283
And if the moose would
pass here.

805
00:49:46.317 --> 00:49:47.751
which I think it's quite likely

806
00:49:47.751 --> 00:49:50.921
because it's really easy
to pass.

807
00:49:50.955 --> 00:49:55.392
I might hear splashes in water.

808
00:49:55.493 --> 00:49:56.961
So yeah.

809
00:49:56.994 --> 00:49:59.630
♪

810
00:49:59.730 --> 00:50:03.100
That's basically it.

811
00:50:03.200 --> 00:50:06.470
I won't do so much
active hunting.

812
00:50:06.504 --> 00:50:08.205
I will always carry
a bow with me

813
00:50:08.239 --> 00:50:10.474
when I go do berry picking.

814
00:50:11.809 --> 00:50:17.081
But beside this.
I'm all set for everything.

815
00:50:17.114 --> 00:50:20.751
♪

816
00:50:23.721 --> 00:50:26.290
[pensive music]

817
00:50:26.323 --> 00:50:32.229
♪

818
00:50:32.263 --> 00:50:34.565
[Will] Good morning.

819
00:50:34.598 --> 00:50:36.367
I slept in my shelter
last night.

820
00:50:36.367 --> 00:50:38.769
Slept just amazing.

821
00:50:38.802 --> 00:50:40.337
I mean.

822
00:50:40.371 --> 00:50:45.309
how cool is that
to be able to sleep in a home

